    <article class="mb-4">
        <div class="container px-4 px-lg-5">
            <div class="row gx-4 gx-lg-5 justify-content-center">
                <div class="col-md-10 col-lg-8 col-xl-7">
                    <h2 class="section-heading">The Beginning:<br>Preparing for the AT </h2>
                    
					<p>So here we are. The beginning of a new adventure. I've decided to hike 2,190 miles across America.</p>
                    <p>I'll be hiking the AT (Appalachian Trail) starting late March to early April, hoping to finish by the end of September.</p>
                    <p>In order to cut down on money, I'll be keeping my "zero" days out of towns and will instead have "nero's" (camping nearby on town days instead of staying in a hotel).</p>
					<p>I'll also pre-cook, dehydrate and vacuum seal all my meals for resupply mail drops, and will attempt to limit my time on trail to 4 months.</p>
					<p>Below is a trail map with a list of all of the AT shelters. I'll be camping next to a different one of these each night along the trail.</p>
					
					<br>
					
					<h3 class="section-heading">Trail Map</h3>
					<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe src="https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/0/embed?mid=1bcu7DtR-KFNHGVEWiyggMMzaevXCF13-" height="650px" width="100%"></iframe></p>
					
                    
					<h3 class="section-heading">Equipment</h3>
					
					<p> Backpack <br> HyperLite Mountain Gear WindRider 3400 - 900g
					<p> Tent <br> Big Agnes Copper Spur HV UL 2 - 1400g </p> 
					<p> Sleep Bag <br> Big Agnes Torchlight UL 20 - 1200g </p>
					<p> Sleep Pad <br> ThermaRest Z Lite Sol - 410g </p>
					<p> Stove System <br> JetBoil Stash - 430g </p> 
					<p> Water Filter <br> Sawyer Squeeze - 85g </p>
					<p> Water Res <br> Camelbak Fusion 3L - 155g </p>
					<br>
					<h5> Total Weight: 
					<br>4580 g / 161.5 oz / 10.1 lbs </h5>
					
					<br>
					
					<h3 class="section-heading">Clothing</h3>

					<p> Rain Jacket <br> Outdoor Research Helium - 179g
					<p> Down Hoody <br> TBD -  Est~ 220g  </p>
					<p> Hiking Pants <br> TBD -  Est~ 200g  </p>
					<p> Hiking Shorts <br> Outdoor Research Ferrosi Shorts - 189g </p>
					<p> Midweight Long-Sleeve Top <br> Helly Hensen Merino Wool Midlayer -  Est~ 160g  </p>
					<p> Midweight Bottoms <br> Helly Hensen Merino Wool Midlayer -  Est~ 180g  </p>					
					<p> Lightweight Hiking Top <br> TBD - Est~ 180g </p>
					<p> Socks <br> 2x Darn Tough Hiker Micro-Crew - 140g </p>
					<br>
					<h5> Total Weight: 
					<br>1448 g / 51.1 oz / 3.2 lbs </h5>
					
					<br>

					
										
					<h3 class="section-heading">Electronics</h3>
					
					<p> Battery Bank <br> NiteCore UL 10,000 - 150g </p>
					<p> Headlamp <br> TBD - Est~ 200g </p>
					<br>
					<h5> Total Weight: 
					<br>350 g / 12.3 oz / 0.8 lbs </h5>
					
					<br>
					
					<h3 class="section-heading">Trail Weight</h3>
					<p> I'm trying my best to keep this as low as possible. In order to be considered a Lightweight Hiker this must be under 20 pounds.</p> 

					<h4>Total Base Weight: 
					<br>6378 g - 225 oz - 14.1 lbs </h4>
					
					<p> I've already surpassed 10 pounds, which is needed to be considered an UltraLight Hiker. Those guys are insane...</p>

					<br>
					
					
                    <h3 class="section-heading">Trail Food</h3>
					
					<p> I plan to save money by dehydrating my own high protien meals, vacuum sealing portions and assembling variety packs. </p>
					<p> I love eating trail meals, however looking at the nutritional information, they are often lacking for the number of calories I'll be burning on trail. The cost for 3-4 of these each day will quickly add up to $45+. </p>
					<p> I know I can do better!!! My goal is to aim for 650 Calories, 50g of Protien at only $5 or less per serving.</p>
					<p> Just got my ChefMan Food Dehydrator and currently running a test with some frozen mixed berries. </p>
					<img src='assets/img/food-001.jpg' style="center" alt="Hydrator" width="300">
					<img src='assets/img/food-002.jpg' style="center" alt="Berries" width="300">
					<br>
					<p>My goal is to pack in as much protein, fat and calories into a variety of 5 or 6 meals that I like a lot. I'll then make these in huge batches that will make up a majority of my meals.</p>
					<p>I'll then also make one off meals that I like, but that I might get sick of eating frequently.  These, I'll only make one batch of 4 or 5 servings, but I'll make a larger number of these. Hopefully around 12.</p>
					<p>My food resupplies will consist a balanced mix, however some will be more protien heavy, some more fruit and veg heavy, and some more carb heavy. This way I can have some control over the boxes I request. </p>
					<p>I'll also have a detailed list of what is in each box with me on the trail so that I can request a specific box. I can then keep track of what I have left for the remainder of the trip, and adjust if necessary with town stops.<p>
					<p> I was expecting to post an update today with a recipe and pictures of the portions, and me placing the food into the dehydrator today, however, I just hit my first setback... Someone threw away my huge batch of chicken and mushroom korma!!!</p> 
					<p>Whelp, nothing I can do about that. I'll head to the store tomorrow and get the ingredients for both a Chicken & Mushroom Korma and a second, as of yet undecided dish. </p>  
					<br>
					<h4 class="nav-link px-lg-3 py-3 py-lg-4"> <a href="at-food.html">Click Here for my Recipes!</a></h4>
					
					<br>
					
					<h3 class="section-heading">Mail Drops</h3>
					<p> There are many businesses along the way that support thru-hikers by holding resupply boxes. </p>
					<p> Below is a spreadsheet I've been creating in order to track the places I can have resupply boxes mailed to myself along the trail. </p>
					<iframe src="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/e/2PACX-1vRmF0dzBjuo9DoLOeDdpVW2GU3GtTYo4UaShUwPieb_6VBsFI-zxL-zGcMbcED_IptzijpdO3fYF0ni/pubhtml?gid=0&amp;single=true&amp;widget=true&amp;headers=false" width="800px" height="500px"></iframe>
					
					<br>
					<p>Drop me a Comment Below!</p>
